from y, allowing us to choose an input-dependent œÑ as a function of V, Cmax that achieves a Œ±-Type I error
guarantee with a fixed Œ± for all inputs. In particular, the Type I error Œ± decreases exponentially as we
increase the threshold œÑ.
C.4
Only true detection (Type II error guarantees)
For bounding the Type II error, i.e., false negative rates, we will work with our proposed method that
generates y from the language model, i.e., sampling from the watermarked distribution ÀÜp recursively one
token at a time.
Let‚Äôs first recall a few notations. h is the input to the language model at step t, i.e., h = [x, y1:t‚àí1]. Let
Œ¥ represent the watermark strength from Equation 1. The green list G ‚äÇ [N] is a random index set of the
vocabulary of size Œ≥N. The watermarked probability distribution ÀÜpt = ÀÜpt(¬∑|h) at time step t. The process of
generating the sentence y1, y2, . . . , yn involves recursively sampling from ÀÜpt, which we refer to as a ‚Äúroll-out‚Äù
procedure.
We need to make a few assumptions about the language model‚Äôs probability distribution p and the prompt x.
We will first state them and then explain why these are natural and arguably needed for the Type II error to
be small.
C.4.1
On-average high entropy assumption
The first such assumption requires the probability of the roll-out to be ‚Äúsufficiently diverse‚Äù on average. We
will introduce the notation ‚à•p‚à•2 :=
qPN
i=1 p[i]2.
Assumption C.8 (On-average-high-entropy). We say a language model‚Äôs probability distribution p with a
prompt x satisfies Œæ-on-average-high-entropy if
1
n
n
X
t=1
E
y1:t‚àí1‚àºp(¬∑|x)[‚à•pt‚à•2] ‚â§ Œæ.
24
This assumption requires the distribution of the roll-out to be sufficiently diffuse on average (either in
expectation or with high probability).
The purpose of these assumptions is to rule out the cases when y1:n is almost deterministic under p and
perturbing the logits by Œ¥ does not change the distribution much at all.
For example, if the prompt writes
‚ÄúGenerate the English alphabet in capital letters for 200 times please.‚Äù
Then the language model would generate
‚ÄúABC...XYZ, ABC...XYZ, ...‚Äù.
Despite that the generated sequence is very long, i.e., n is as large as 5, 200, the added watermark does not
change the distribution very much at all. To see this, if p(y3 = ‚ÄúC‚Äù|x, h) ‚â• 1 ‚àí œµ for a tiny œµ, and then by our
quality guarantee, ÀÜp(y3 = ‚ÄúC‚Äù |x, h) ‚â• 1 ‚àí œµeŒ¥.
Quantitatively, for nearly uniform pt, Œæ = O(1/N), if pt concentrates on a single token for all t, e.g., when a
football commentator exclaims ‚ÄúGoal goal goal goal ....‚Äù, then we cannot obtain a better bound than
the trivial Œæ ‚â§ 1. In the alphabet example above Œæ ‚â§ 1/26.
Why is it called entropy? Assumption C.8 is related to the ‚Äúhigh-entropy‚Äù assumption in Kirchenbauer
et al. [2023] but for a slightly different kind of entropy. In a more formal sense, the quantity ‚à•pt‚à•2 is connected
to the Tsallis entropy of order 2, defined as S2(pt) = kB(1 ‚àí ‚à•pt‚à•2) where kB is known as the Boltzmann
constant. Our assumption requires the expected Tsallis entropy of the conditional distribution pt over the
roll-out of p to be larger than kB(1 ‚àí Œæ) on average among t = 1, ..., n.
For a high-probability result, we also need a stronger version.
Assumption C.9 (On-average-high-entropy (high probability)). We say that a language model‚Äôs probability
distribution p with a prompt x satisfies (Œæ, Œ≤)-on-average-high-entropy if with probability at least 1 ‚àí Œ≤ over
the generated sequence y1:n,
