C.4.2
A ‚Äúhomophily‚Äù assumption
The second assumption that we need to make is called ‚Äúhomophily‚Äù, which says that increasing the probability
of a group of tokens by adding the watermarks will not decrease the probability of generating the same group
of tokens in the future as the language model rolls out.
Assumption C.11 (‚ÄúHomophily‚Äù). We say a language model‚Äôs probability distribution p and prompt x
satisfy ‚Äúhomophily‚Äù if for any G, the corresponding watermarked ÀÜp satisfies that
E
h‚àºÀÜp(¬∑|x)

P
y‚àºÀÜp(¬∑|h,x)(y ‚àà G)

‚â•
E
h‚àºp(¬∑|x)

P
y‚àºÀÜp(¬∑|h,x)(y ‚àà G)

where h denotes the generated sequence before y.
This assumption says that by increasing the probability of tokens in G, the induced distribution of the prefix
h cannot counter-intuitively reduce the probability of tokens in G in the future on average.
The assumption is not unreasonable, because we expect a language model to be more likely to refer to text it
has generated in the prefix than those that did not appear in the prefix.
This ‚Äúhomophily‚Äù assumption is needed to rule out the unnatural situation where increasing the green list
tokens initially ends up reducing the number of green list tokens in the long run. To illustrate this, consider
the following example utilizing the prompt:
x = ‚ÄúRandomly select a color, state what it is.
Then write a short poem about it without
naming this color at all.‚Äù
The generated text from a commercial language model is
‚ÄúColor choice:
green.
Emerald whispers in the meadow‚Äôs sway, Life‚Äôs verdant rhythm in
ceaseless play.
It cradles the world in a leafy embrace, A silent serenade to nature‚Äôs
grace.‚Äù
Notice that if the token ‚Äúgreen‚Äù ‚àà G, it increases the probability of the language model generating ‚Äúgreen‚Äù
at the beginning. However, regardless of the text‚Äôs length, the subsequent portion of the generated text will
not contain the word ‚Äúgreen‚Äù, as instructed by the prompt. This decreases the expected number of times the
token ‚Äúgreen‚Äù appears.
To hammer it home, consider the following more quantitative construction of that works no matter which
random green list G realizes.
x = ‚ÄúChoose the first k token by random sampling without replacement.
Then sample from
all but the token you choose uniformly for n-k rounds.‚Äù
It‚Äôs easy to calculate that the expected number of times any token appears in a language model that perfectly
follows the instruction will be n/N. However, the watermarked language model, let‚Äôs say we use a very large
Œ¥ such that the first k tokens are from the green list, then the expected number of times a green-list token
appears is
k
Œ≥N + Œ≥N‚àík
Œ≥N
