Remark C.14 (Exponentially small Type I and Type II error guarantees). Recall that according to Theorem C.4,
in order to have a false positive rate controlled at level Œ±, we need to set the threshold œÑ ‚â≥
p
log(1/Œ±) for
sufficiently high-entropy sequences. Theorem C.13 says that if we want the false negative rate to be smaller
than Œ≤, we only need the threshold œÑ ‚â≤ Œ∫Œ¥n under similar (slightly different) high-entropy sequences for
n ‚â≥ log(1/Œ≤)/Œ¥2. Observe that there is a wide range of valid choices of œÑ for us to have a detection algorithm
that does not make Type I or Type II error with high probability. These observations together suggest that
we can afford to choose Œ¥ ‚âç 1/‚àön if the sequence is sufficiently high-entropy.
Remark C.15 (Information-theoretic optimality). The sample complexity of n ‚â≥ 1/Œ¥2 is information-
theoretically optimal (up to a logarithmic factor) in Œ¥ because, our accuracy guarantee (together with
the composition theorem) indicates that the KL-divergence between a sequence of length n generated from
p and that generated from ÀÜp is nŒ¥2 indistinguishable, i.e., n > 1/Œ¥2 for any classifier ‚Äî even the uniform
most-powerful Neyman-Pearson likelihood-ratio test (which requires additional information, e.g., x and p
which we do not have) ‚Äî to make no mistakes with a constant probability.
